WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.400
 I mentioned that JavaScript owns the document object model.

00:00:03.400 --> 00:00:05.980
 The document object model is what we see

00:00:05.980 --> 00:00:07.520
 when we're looking at the browser.

00:00:07.520 --> 00:00:09.860
 A browser parses the HTML, sometimes our JavaScript

00:00:09.860 --> 00:00:12.720
 writes it and then creates this object,

00:00:12.720 --> 00:00:14.600
 we call the document object model,

00:00:14.600 --> 00:00:16.720
 which is then displayed to the user through a window.

00:00:16.720 --> 00:00:19.440
 A window is the subset of the document object model.

00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:22.380
 In whatever JavaScript we write,

00:00:22.380 --> 00:00:25.200
 we can read, manipulate, and update the DOM.

00:00:25.200 --> 00:00:26.880
 And as soon as the DOM is updated,

00:00:26.880 --> 00:00:30.080
 the user sees the updates through the window.

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:32.480
 And we can also just go into the debugger

00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:36.220
 and directly manipulate the document object model.

00:00:36.220 --> 00:00:38.560
 So if we go back to the 01 NoScript,

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:40.400
 there's no JavaScript in here.

00:00:40.400 --> 00:00:44.080
 So you just go, it shows you a header and a paragraph,

00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:45.620
 and that's the document object model.

00:00:45.620 --> 00:00:48.920
 But you'll note that if you go into Inspect Element

00:00:48.920 --> 00:00:51.300
 and then go into that paragraph tag,

00:00:51.300 --> 00:00:53.740
 you can change and add the word cool.

00:00:55.320 --> 00:00:57.920
 In a sense the debugger is JavaScript, right?

00:00:57.920 --> 00:01:00.480
 And you can actually type JavaScript commands

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:03.480
 into the debugger if you do the right thing.

00:01:03.480 --> 00:01:06.880
 But the debugger is owning

00:01:06.880 --> 00:01:08.440
 the document object model as well.

00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:11.120
 And so you simply can change the document object model.

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:14.440
 And literally, it changes the UI,

00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:16.600
 but truly the document object model changes.

00:01:16.600 --> 00:01:18.560
 So you can take a, you can even change

00:01:18.560 --> 00:01:20.080
 the kind of a tag you're dealing with.

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:21.680
 You could turn this into an anchor tag,

00:01:21.680 --> 00:01:23.160
 you could add some hrefs.

00:01:23.160 --> 00:01:26.280
 You can change the document object model.

00:01:26.280 --> 00:01:31.160
 You're displayed, it just, you change it and you see it.

00:01:31.160 --> 00:01:33.680
 Now, I mentioned this thing called the window.

00:01:33.680 --> 00:01:36.920
 There are two sort of foundational objects

00:01:36.920 --> 00:01:38.280
 in JavaScript in the browser.

00:01:38.280 --> 00:01:42.280
 There's the DOM, and the DOM is an abstraction.

00:01:42.280 --> 00:01:46.480
 It is a structured hierarchy of tags, we call them elements.

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:50.080
 The window is how we see it.

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:52.960
 So you can think of this picture that I've been showing you

00:01:52.960 --> 00:01:55.880
 of parsing the response, running some JavaScript,

00:01:55.880 --> 00:01:58.520
 and tweaking the document object model

00:01:58.520 --> 00:02:00.960
 and showing it to the user.

00:02:00.960 --> 00:02:02.680
 And if you change the document object model,

00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:03.960
 it's immediately updated.

00:02:03.960 --> 00:02:07.400
 On the left, that's a kind of an oversimplification

00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:12.080
 because the way we actually view the document object model

00:02:12.080 --> 00:02:14.320
 is through the window.

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:16.280
 The window is what's on your screen.

00:02:16.280 --> 00:02:20.120
 And probably the most easy way to demonstrate this

00:02:20.120 --> 00:02:22.560
 is to understand that the document object model

00:02:22.560 --> 00:02:26.200
 could be very large and the window could be very small.

00:02:26.200 --> 00:02:28.160
 And the document object model doesn't change

00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:31.120
 and you can resize the window back and forth.

00:02:31.120 --> 00:02:33.400
 So sometimes you see scroll bars.

00:02:33.400 --> 00:02:37.960
 The scroll bar is not a notion in the document object model,

00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:39.680
 it's a notion in the window.

00:02:39.680 --> 00:02:41.440
 The window has a certain height,

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:44.840
 the document object model may or may not completely fit

00:02:44.840 --> 00:02:48.280
 in the window, and that has to do with the window height

00:02:48.280 --> 00:02:50.280
 and so scroll bars.

00:02:50.280 --> 00:02:55.240
 And so for example, if you look at 06height.html,

00:02:55.240 --> 00:02:58.120
 all it does is puts out the header, puts out the paragraph,

00:02:58.120 --> 00:03:01.960
 and then prints out window height and window width,

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:04.480
 window.innerHeight and window.innerWidth.

00:03:04.480 --> 00:03:09.320
 These are the height of the window,

00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:10.600
 not the document object model,

00:03:10.600 --> 00:03:12.720
 but the window through which we're viewing it.

00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:16.400
 And so if you show this page with the debugger turned on

00:03:16.400 --> 00:03:19.120
 with a really tiny window,

00:03:19.120 --> 00:03:21.280
 it says that the height is 116.

00:03:21.280 --> 00:03:23.080
 If you make the window bigger and hit reload,

00:03:23.080 --> 00:03:24.960
 it says the height's 256.

00:03:24.960 --> 00:03:29.600
 So in JavaScript, we can ask questions about the window

00:03:29.600 --> 00:03:30.920
 and we can do things to the window.

00:03:30.920 --> 00:03:33.000
 One thing we could do is we could scroll it up and down

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:35.760
 and that's actually a common thing to do in JavaScript.

00:03:35.760 --> 00:03:37.440
 If you have a big document object model

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:38.480
 and you got a scroll window

00:03:38.480 --> 00:03:41.040
 and you wanna show the user a particular thing

00:03:41.040 --> 00:03:42.920
 like go to bottom,

00:03:42.920 --> 00:03:46.400
 JavaScript can scroll the window down to the bottom

00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:50.160
 or up or down, I don't get those right very well,

00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:53.520
 but we can control the window.

00:03:53.520 --> 00:03:56.080
 In this case, we're simply asking it how tall you are

00:03:56.080 --> 00:03:56.960
 and how wide you are,

00:03:56.960 --> 00:03:58.440
 but we can also control it.

00:03:58.440 --> 00:04:04.000
 And so if we take a look now and we make 07scroll.htm,

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.280
 we can see that we have nine paragraphs and a header.

00:04:07.280 --> 00:04:10.960
 That is the actual content, okay?

00:04:10.960 --> 00:04:12.440
 And if we have a tall window,

00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:13.920
 we can see the whole document.

00:04:13.920 --> 00:04:15.640
 But if we make the window smaller,

00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:19.200
 then we can only see a subset of the document object model.

00:04:19.200 --> 00:04:21.480
 So the window height changes

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:23.160
 and if you look, you now have a scroll bar

00:04:23.160 --> 00:04:24.440
 and what does the scroll bar do?

00:04:24.440 --> 00:04:27.360
 Well, it just takes and moves the document object model

00:04:27.360 --> 00:04:28.520
 up and down.

00:04:28.520 --> 00:04:31.120
 Well, it moves the part of the document object,

00:04:31.120 --> 00:04:33.720
 our view to the document object model up and down.

00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:36.240
 But if you're doing an inspect element in some browsers,

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:38.640
 you will see that it's telling us

00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:40.680
 with little kind of annotations

00:04:40.680 --> 00:04:43.640
 that the body is being scrolled right now

00:04:43.640 --> 00:04:46.960
 and up through paragraph four is overflowed

00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:50.760
 off the screen up and paragraph seven, eight, and nine

00:04:50.760 --> 00:04:53.080
 have overflowed and they've gone off the screen below.

00:04:53.080 --> 00:04:55.840
 Now, if you play with this and you resize it

00:04:55.840 --> 00:04:57.600
 and refresh it and resize it and refresh it,

00:04:57.600 --> 00:04:59.840
 you'll see this whole, I mean, you don't,

00:04:59.840 --> 00:05:01.440
 on the left, the whole thing shows

00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:04.960
 and so body is not indicated as the scrollable element.

00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:08.960
 And the headers not overflow, et cetera.

00:05:08.960 --> 00:05:10.280
 So you can play with this,

00:05:10.280 --> 00:05:12.440
 but play with it with different sizes, refresh it,

00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:15.120
 and then inspect element and watch how the scroll,

00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:17.640
 the overflow, and the scroll bar.

00:05:17.640 --> 00:05:19.120
 And in this case, I'm not printing out height,

00:05:19.120 --> 00:05:20.880
 but you would be seeing that the height

00:05:20.880 --> 00:05:22.640
 would actually change.

00:05:22.640 --> 00:05:25.280
 So one of the things that we're gonna do next

00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:28.480
 is we're gonna modify the document object model

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:29.880
 in JavaScript.

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:32.460
 (upbeat music)

